Australian, N.Z. Stocks: Alumina, BHP, David Jones, Telstra

-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 
2011-08-11T06:37:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-11/australian-n-z-stocks-bhp-david-jones-rio-santos-telstra.html
Australia ’s S&P/ASX 200 Index was
little changed at 4,140.8 at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading in
Sydney, reversing an earlier loss of as much as 2 percent.  New
Zealand ’s  NZX 50 Index (NZSE50FG)  gained 0.8 percent to 3,208.62 in
Wellington.  The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  Mining companies: A measure of primary metals traded in
 London  fell for a sixth straight day yesterday, losing 1 percent
amid concern that  Europe  will fail to contain its debt crisis.
Copper futures dropped 2.1 percent in  New York ,  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s No. 1 mining
company, fell 1.2 percent to A$37.93. BHP and Nyrstar NV failed
to reach agreement in talks on a joint bid for Lundin Mining
Corp., two people familiar with the matter said.  Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the world’s second-largest mining
company by sales, lost 2.7 percent to A$70.41.  Alumina Ltd. (AWC)  , partner in the world’s biggest
producer of the material used to make aluminum, slumped 5.8
percent to A$1.79 even after saying first-half profit climbed 53
percent.  Gold producers: Gold futures extended a rally to a record,
gaining 2.4 percent in New York yesterday on mounting demand for
a haven as global equities plunged amid escalating U.S. and
European debt woes.  Newcrest Mining Ltd. (NCM)  , Australia’s biggest gold
producer, gained 3.8 percent to A$40.74. St Barbara Ltd. (SBM
AU), a smaller miner, rose 3.8 percent to A$1.935.  Bank shares: Banks climbed after a report that showed the
jobless rate rose sparked speculation the central bank may cut
 interest rates . Goldman Sachs & Partners Australia Pty revised
its forecast for Australia’s central bank policy, predicting it
will lower its benchmark overnight cash rate target by as much
as 50 basis points before the end of the year.  Westpac Banking Corp. (WBC)  , Australia’s No. 2 lender by
market value, rose 1.5 percent to A$20.45, reversing an earlier
decline of as much as 2.6 percent.  Australia & New Zealand
Banking Group Ltd. (ANZ)   advanced 1.5 percent to A$20.09.        David Jones Ltd. (DJS)   slumped 6.4 percent to A$2.62.
The nation’s second-largest department store chain reported that
second-half same store sales declined 6.9 percent, not the 6.2
percent disclosed in an earlier press release, according to a
regulatory filing.  Telstra Corp. (TLS AU) gained 5.7 percent to AS$2.99.
Australia’s largest telephone company posted second-half
earnings that beat analyst estimates after winning mobile
customers and cutting operating costs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Shani Raja in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editors responsible for this story:
